{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:12:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20877"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13752"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11592"},{"type":"tags","id":"11593"},{"type":"tags","id":"12700"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33116"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of structural variations in protein-coding genes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They are less common in cancer than point mutations","They occur exclusively in germline cells","They always result in loss of protein function","They cannot be detected by next-generation sequencing","They can include copy number changes and translocations"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey can include copy number changes and translocations\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Structural variations in protein-coding genes encompass both copy number alterations (amplifications or deletions) and chromosomal rearrangements like translocations. These changes can result in either gain or loss of protein function, depending on the specific alteration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are less common in cancer than point mutations\u003C/strong\u003E - Structural variations are actually quite common in cancer. Many cancers are characterized by specific structural variations, such as the Philadelphia chromosome in chronic myeloid leukaemia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey occur exclusively in germline cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Structural variations can occur in both germline cells (inherited) and somatic cells (acquired). Somatic structural variations are particularly common in cancer.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey always result in loss of protein function\u003C/strong\u003E - Structural variations can result in either gain or loss of function. For example, gene amplifications often lead to increased protein expression and function.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey cannot be detected by next-generation sequencing\u003C/strong\u003E - Next-generation sequencing (NGS) technology is actually highly effective at detecting structural variations and has enabled the discovery of potentially pathogenic structural alterations in many disorders.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA classic example of a structural variation is the Philadelphia chromosome, which is a translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22 resulting in the fusion of the \u003Cem\u003EBCR\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EABL\u003C/em\u003E genes. This translocation is characteristic of chronic myeloid leukaemia and results in constitutive activation of the ABL tyrosine kinase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Structural variations in protein-coding genes include copy number changes (amplifications or deletions) and translocations that can result in aberrant protein function.","Structural alterations can occur in germline cells or be acquired in somatic tissues, with germline alterations often involving contiguous portions of chromosomes.","Next-generation sequencing technology has enabled detection of potentially pathogenic structural alterations in common disorders such as autism.","Cancers frequently contain somatically acquired structural alterations, with the Philadelphia chromosome (BCR-ABL translocation) being a classic example in chronic myeloid leukaemia."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 143"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20877"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T11:52:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T11:52:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13752"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic 